### Markdown Description

```markdown
# Reduced Hubble constant/"little h" Equivalency

The dimensionless version of the Hubble constant - often known as "little h" - is a frequently-used quantity in extra-galactic astrophysics. It is also widely known as the bane of beginners' existence in such fields (See e.g., this paper, which also provides valuable advice on the use of little h). Astropy provides an equivalence that helps keep this straight in at least some of these cases, by providing a way to convert to/from physical to "little h" units. Two example conversions:

```python
import astropy.units as u
H0_70 = 70 * u.km/u.s / u.Mpc
distance = 100 * (u.Mpc/u.littleh)  # Convert distance from Mpc to littleh
luminosity = 1 * u.Lsun * u.littleh**-2  # Convert luminosity from Lsun to littleh

# Convert luminosity to Lsun, using H0_70
luminosity.to(u.Lsun, u.with_H0(H0_70))
```

Note the unit name "littleh" - while this unit is usually expressed in the literature as just h, here it is "littleh" to not cause confusion with "hours".

If no argument is given (or the argument is None), this equivalence assumes the H0 from the current default cosmology:

```python
distance = 100 * (u.Mpc/u.littleh)
distance.to(u.Mpc, u.with_H0())
```
